segments.text: These buildings were constructed with brick or clay tile-bearing walls where parapets are not secured to the roofs and floors
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: making them vulnerable to earthquakes.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: In the four years following that report, I worked with the mayor's office, the state legislature, Office of Emergency Management, Seattle Department of Construction and Inspection, and community partners like the Alliance for Safety, Affordability, and Preservation, otherwise known as ASAP, to build towards an approved 2021 city council resolution.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: That resolution represented a joint
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: commitment by the mayor and the council to work on developing a phased mandatory seismic retrofit program.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: Led by this resolution, SDCI has since hired a URM program manager who has in turn led the department to release the 2023 draft URM retrofit technical standard and director's rule.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: These outline pathways for URM property owners to begin
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: Moving towards compliance with forthcoming mandatory URM retrofit requirements.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: Again, these mandatory requirements are not in place yet.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: But what this resolution does is it creates an interim step before those mandatory requirements are ready to be adopted.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: And it provides transparency to property owners and states the city intends to use this technical standard as compliance as a compliance standard in future legislation.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: And that next step is actually going to be a voluntary comply requirement or.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: opportunity, a voluntary program to allow property owners before the mandatory program goes into effect to voluntarily come into compliance using this technical standard.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: Again, allowing some property owners to voluntarily comply and stop work or start work
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: earlier, I think is perceived by many, particularly those in the community that are members of ASAP, as helpful to the overall effort.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: Of course, as we know, yesterday evening we received a reminder that earthquakes are unpredictable.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: We are fortunate that last night our region only experienced a small earthquake, but we know
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_31

segments.text: that the big one can happen at any point, and the sooner we can get our buildings into compliance, the sooner we can protect the residents and neighbors of these buildings.
